    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1896-01-16T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1896-01-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="732"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d732">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">
                        <persName type="from">Mavroyeni Bey</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to"
                            >Olney</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Translation.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Turkish Legation</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1896-01-16">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 16, 1896</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Mr. <hi rend="smallcaps">Secretary of State</hi>: His Excellency Tevfik Pasha has
                    just informed me that the Sublime Porte regrets that it can not comply with Mr.
                    Terrell’s request for permission for the <hi rend="italic">Bancroft</hi> to pass
                    through the strait, that vessel having been authorized to remain at the disposal
                    of the United States legation at Constantinople.</p>
                <p>Your excellency knows perfectly well the earnest and sincere desire of the
                    Imperial Government to do all in its power to strengthen if possible the ties of
                    friendship which unite the two countries, but in this case a certain fact is
                    involved, to wit, that only the signatory Powers of the treaty of Paris enjoy
                    the right to have vessels of war permanently at Constantinople at the orders of
                    their respective embassies. Now, the United States Government does not appear in
                    the number of the signatories of that treaty. I am, consequently, sure that your
                    excellency will be pleased to take the foregoing into consideration.</p>
                <p>Accept, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Mavroyeni.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
